{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The real failure boundary includes Git’s actual rename detection plus the CLI’s parsing/classification path. A mock diff can miss real rename heuristics and subprocess output differences, so REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE point to System. Integration was considered but rejected because the behavior explicitly depends on reading a real git repository state. Agentic/Workflow are disqualified because no AI/ML step is involved.","test_description":"Create a temporary real git repo, commit a file, rename it (`git mv`) and commit/update changes, run the CLI as a subprocess, and assert the report shows the file only under `renamed` and not under `added` or `deleted`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.67,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Binary diff handling often fails at real subprocess/encoding boundaries (e.g., Git binary diff markers, byte handling, stdout decoding). In-process stubs may not reproduce those exact conditions, so REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE require System. Integration was considered but rejected because behavior text explicitly requires handling real binary diffs from repository analysis. Agentic/Workflow are disqualified: no model output quality is involved.","test_description":"In a temporary real git repo, add/modify a binary file (e.g., random bytes), run the CLI via subprocess, verify process exit is successful, and assert binary files are included in counts/category output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.74,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This failure commonly appears when Git commands run against an unborn `HEAD` and return real exit codes/messages. That is a subprocess + real repo state boundary, so System is the minimum. Integration was considered but rejected because faking repository state would not fully validate actual Git error-mode behavior. Agentic/Workflow are disqualified by behavior text (pure git/CLI behavior).","test_description":"Initialize a new temp git repo with no commits, run the CLI subprocess, assert zero/empty structured report on stdout and no error exit/crash.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.69,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This validates end-to-end correctness against real Git history semantics across adds/deletes/renames/modifies. Mocked history can hide mismatches caused by real git command behavior, rev/range handling, and parsing under subprocess I/O, so System is required. Integration was considered but rejected because behavior text requires matching actual repository history. Agentic/Workflow are disqualified (no AI-dependent correctness).","test_description":"Construct a temp repo with a known sequence of commits producing controlled added/deleted/renamed/modified events; run the CLI subprocess for the same history window; assert output counts exactly match independently computed expected counts from git history.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.76,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Staged vs unstaged behavior depends on real Git index/worktree semantics, which are OS/filesystem + subprocess interactions. A mock can easily miss index edge cases, so REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE indicate System. Integration was considered but rejected because the behavior explicitly compares real staged and unstaged repository states. Agentic/Workflow are disqualified since no LLM/ML decision is part of execution.","test_description":"In a temp real git repo, create equivalent content changes once as unstaged and once staged, run CLI subprocess in both states, and assert structured stdout outputs are byte-for-byte identical.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.81,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
